  "indianapolis-in": {
    atticStrategyPara: "Indianapolis neighborhoods such as Irvington, Fountain Square, and Butler-Tarkington sit on a mix of slab-on-grade and unfinished-basement foundations that funnel stack-effect air through the attic. Blown cellulose at 11-14 inches (R-38 to R-49) is the workhorse solution because it fills around truss webs and HVAC boots that rigid batts miss. Homes built before 1960 along Meridian Street often have original rock-wool batts compressed to 2 inches, delivering under R-7, making full removal and replacement the cost-effective path.",
    wallStrategyPara: "Marion County's post-war housing boom produced thousands of 2x4 stud-wall ranches with R-0 to R-7 fiberglass. Drill-and-fill dense-pack cellulose at 3.5 lb/ft3 is the standard retrofit for frame walls. Double-wythe brick homes in Herron-Morton Place and Woodruff Place cannot accept exterior rigid foam without altering the masonry profile, so interior 2-inch XPS with a thermal break at studs is the compliant alternative under Indiana residential code IRC N1102.",
    airSealingPara: "Indianapolis blower-door baselines on 1940-1970 homes typically land between 3,200 and 5,800 CFM50, driven by open balloon-frame cavities and unlined chimney chases. The highest-ROI seal points are the attic top plate, recessed light cans (IC-rated retrofit covers), and the band joist at the basement ceiling. Indianapolis Energy Auditors Association members report that air sealing alone delivers 12-18% heating savings before any insulation upgrade.",
    rebatePara: "CenterPoint Energy Indiana (formerly Vectren) and Indianapolis Power & Light (IPL) both run weatherization incentive programs for Marion County homeowners. IPL's Home Energy Rebate covers up to $500 toward insulation and air sealing. The federal 25C credit at 30% up to $1,200 stacks with state rebates. Indiana's low-income LIHEAP weatherization program processes roughly 4,000 homes per year statewide.",
    contractorLandscapePara: "The Indianapolis metro supports three contractor tiers: franchise operations (Dr. Energy Saver, USA Insulation) handling volume attic work, independent BPI-certified auditor-installers focused on whole-house performance, and spray-foam specialists serving new construction and crawlspace encapsulation. Marion County requires a general contractor license or specialty trade registration. Expect $1.00-$1.50 per sqft for blown cellulose attic top-up on a 1,500 sqft ceiling.",
    commonUpsellPara: "Spray-foam contractors in Indianapolis frequently pitch closed-cell foam on attic rafters at $6.00-$8.50 per sqft for a conditioned-attic conversion. This only pays off when the air handler and full duct run live in the attic space. A more common legitimate add-on is crawlspace encapsulation with 2-inch closed-cell on the band joist and a 20-mil vapor barrier on the floor, typically $3,500-$6,000 for a 1,000 sqft crawl. Watch for upsells on radiant barriers, which have negligible value in a heating-dominant Zone 5A climate.",
    historicHomePara: "Irvington Historic District and Lockerbie Square impose exterior-alteration review through the Indianapolis Historic Preservation Commission (IHPC). Interior insulation work is unrestricted. Lockerbie's 1870s shotgun houses often have no wall insulation at all, making dense-pack cellulose through closet-side access holes the go-to method. Knob-and-tube wiring is present in roughly 15% of pre-1925 Indianapolis homes and must be decommissioned before cavity insulation per Indiana fire code.",
    codeSnapshotPara: "Indianapolis enforces the 2012 Indiana Energy Conservation Code based on IECC 2012 with state amendments. Prescriptive attic minimums are R-49 and wall minimums are R-20 or R-13+5ci for Zone 5A new construction. Retrofit trigger is opening more than 30% of a given envelope assembly. The City-County Building permit office on City Market Square processes residential insulation permits within 5-7 business days.",
    monitoringPara: "IPL and CenterPoint both provide 13-month billing history exports for pre-retrofit baselining. Indianapolis home energy auditors typically use a calibrated blower door with DG-1000 manometer. Post-retrofit targets for a comprehensive insulation-plus-sealing job in Marion County are 0.25 CFM50 per sqft of envelope area and a 30-40% reduction in heating therms.",
    moistureControlPara: "Indianapolis receives 42 inches of annual precipitation and winter interior humidity can push above 40% with tight envelopes. Kraft-faced batts with the kraft toward conditioned space remain the default vapor retarder for attic floor installations. For cathedral ceiling retrofits, Intello Plus smart membranes handle the seasonal humidity swing. Crawlspace retrofits in Fountain Square and Garfield Park require a ground-contact vapor barrier plus perimeter drainage to avoid bulk water issues."
  },

